Why this is better

Because now:

DIM_PROVIDER = provider master
DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY = provider specialty
DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP = specialty meaning/description

So together these 3 tables can tell you:

provider id
provider name
NPI
PCP indicator
specialty code
specialty description
specialty type

That is exactly what you need.

Very useful point: PCP_IND

This column is especially helpful:

PCP_IND

This may already tell you whether the provider is a PCP.

So instead of only relying on specialty exclusions, you may be able to use:

PCP_IND = 'Y' or similar for PCP
non-PCP for specialist

You should first inspect the values.

Run:

SELECT
    PCP_IND,
    COUNT(*) AS CNT
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER
GROUP BY PCP_IND
ORDER BY PCP_IND;

This will show whether values are like:

Y / N
1 / 0
something else
Best next query to run

This is a great validation query:

SELECT
    p.PROVIDER_ID,
    p.PROVIDER_FULL_NAME,
    p.NPI_ID,
    p.PCP_IND,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
LIMIT 100;

If this returns rows, then your provider-specialty setup is working.

How to identify specialist using this

You now have 2 possible ways:

Option 1: Use PCP_IND

If PCP_IND is reliable:

PCP = PCP_IND = 'Y'
Specialist = not PCP

Example:

WHERE NVL(p.PCP_IND, 'N') <> 'Y'
Option 2: Use specialty type / description

If lookup table has:

PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC

then you can identify:

Family Practice
Internal Medicine
General Practice
as PCP

and everything else as specialist.

Even better: use both

Best practice is often:

use PCP_IND
validate with specialty description/type

Example:

if PCP_IND = 'Y', definitely PCP
if specialty description says cardiology/dermatology/etc., specialist
Stronger query for review
SELECT DISTINCT
    p.PROVIDER_ID,
    p.PROVIDER_FULL_NAME,
    p.NPI_ID,
    p.PCP_IND,
    s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_DESC,
    l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_TYPE
FROM FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER p
JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY s
    ON p.PROVIDER_ID = s.PROVIDER_ID
LEFT JOIN FWRB_PRD_WMIDR_DB.BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_LKP l
    ON s.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE = l.PROVIDER_SPECIALTY_CODE
WHERE p.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
  AND s.ACTIVE_FLAG = 1
ORDER BY p.PROVIDER_ID
LIMIT 200;
What this means for your specialist-visit logic

Now your likely logic is:

find visit CPT/HCPCS codes
join claims to DIM_PROVIDER using claim provider id
join DIM_PROVIDER to DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY
join to specialty lookup
exclude PCP providers or include only specialists
Important thing to confirm next

Now the next question is:

Does your claims table use this same BI_ANALYSIS.DIM_PROVIDER.PROVIDER_ID?

If yes, then you are in great shape.

If the claim table has provider-related columns like:

rendering provider id
billing provider id
servicing provider id

and one of those equals DIM_PROVIDER.PROVIDER_ID, then you can build the final specialist visit query.

Short answer

Yes — DIM_PROVIDER has both provider name and NPI_ID, and it is much more likely to join correctly with DIM_PROVIDER_SPECIALTY because both use the same numeric PROVIDER_ID.

